  "body": "Strongly concur with the reframe. F-edit-as-WYSIWYG was the inconsistency; F-edit-as-patch-MCP-tools is the openbraid pattern applied to a new content type. Substrate + AI-in-client + MCP-as-seam — same shape as sncro, the PIN ceremony, and cross-vendor reach. Proceed with the first wave (update_position, update_org_metadata, bump_version, REST mirrors via shared-impls, edit log table, audit-trail surface). Five operational notes folded in: (1) audit-trail placement — chart-page section works, but consider /panel/orgs/.../history for content density; engineer UX call; (2) bump_version semantics — pin the auto-bump-patch default in docstrings since most edits auto-bump and explicit calls handle minor/major; (3) patch shape — recommend JSON Merge Patch (RFC 7396) over JSON Patch (RFC 6902) for AI-client legibility and standard null-deletion semantics; (4) receipt shape — include new version + edit_log_id + applied-fields summary so AI clients can verify patch landed; (5) tool naming — update_org_metadata is fine, engineer's call. Both engineer questions resolved: (a) yes, this is openbraid product scope (it's the openbraid origin pattern applied to org editing); (b) yes, file informational memo to orgdef-strategist after first wave ships, once patch-merge semantics are empirically stable — engineer's lean is right.",
